segments.text: This is January 11, 1981, an interview with Tom Wetzel, landscape architect, graduate of Texas A&M in the Department of Urban and Regional Planning, as well as the Department of Landscape Architecture.
Tom has been living in Austin for three years, and it's with this in mind and his particular perception of the physical environment
that he may be able to provide a particular insight into the planning process in Austin as he has come to know it.
Tom, would you like to give us a bit of information about your firm, perhaps to begin with, and the project that you've been working on for Austin?
That might be a good place to begin.
I'm with Myrick Newman-Dahlberg, who are landscape architects and urban planners.
We are presently working on a project titled the Lower Waller Creek Development, which is a city project of the redevelopment of the Waller Creek segment between 11th Street and Town Lake.
This segment of the creek has been historically basically a sewer.
And the objective is to develop a hike and bike trail promenade walkway from Symphony Square at 11th Street to Town Lake.
The project was begun in approximately 1975 with authorization from the Friedman Council to develop a comprehensive study of the entire area that would develop a direction
for planning and opportunities, or at least to point out opportunities, in this eastern side of the Central Business District.

The project progressed through 1975 with the culmination of a planning study by the joint venture consultants of Myrick, Newman, Dahlberg, Taniguchi, Scheffelman, Minter, Vacker, and Fries and Nichols.
The three consultants, landscape architects, architects and engineers, developed a comprehensive plan for the Lower Wall Creek area, which included all aspects of urban design.
The project is now under its first phase of construction, which is
approximately a 1.5 million dollar bond funds used by the city for this particular project.
No federal funds are involved.
Subsequent phases of the project would include flood water diversion and other amenities along the creek.
Already there has been a

increase in the activity of real estate along the creek as more and more local developers realize the potential of the creek area once the city has taken the initial step to clean up and to provide some amenities that will attract local residents to the area.
Thomas, could you go into the origins of the project?
The spark plugged the thing initially.
Was it an individual or a commission?
And who do you report to as a consortium in City Hall?
Who is managing the project for the city?
The initial planning on the project occurred prior to my employment with Myrick Newman Dahlberg.
And so I guess I'm truthfully only sketchy on those details.

The potential of Waller Creek has been a famous or infamous planning and architecture study for the University of Texas architecture department for many, many years, as well as the town lake development was, similar to the large Trinity Lake proposal for downtown Dallas, where they would redevelop the Trinity River channel.
So the history of the project, I guess, probably goes back maybe 40 years in Austin's history.
People have been concerned about the creek.
But it wasn't until the Friedman Council, who was probably the most environmentally oriented council that this city has ever seen, it wasn't until that council that real action and steps were taken.
As far as us as consultants,

Our dealings from the planning stage through this construction phase have been basically with originally what was called the Building Construction Department, which is now part of Public Works, and the prime client is the Parks and Recreation Department.

In fact, any kinds of changes during this construction phase, we first consult with Parks and Recreation as to our recommendation, and basically Public Works is a functionary and sees that it occurs, you know, the actual construction.
Very good.
There has been, since the early planning stages of the project in 75, there has been a change in the city council.
There has been a tremendous change in the city council as far as direction and their interest or concern about development.
And there has been a change within the city staff of reorganization nature, which has really complicated the project as far as consultants are concerned.
And many of the city staff who originally had

provided planning direction are no longer with the city or have changed departments completely and have nothing to do with it and this as consultants frequently leaves us out in the cold in trying to either justify a particular design decision or whatever the circumstance may be it's not necessarily a perfect working arrangement well

Thomas, going on to the major planning thrust of Austin, taking a look at what has been happening in the recent past that you feel comfortable and knowledgeable about discussing, would you care to comment on the character of the planning

activities in Austin with regard to any aspects of it that might occur to you, such as transportation, environmental quality, growth control, growth management, new industry, human services, whatever might be indicated.
It appears that the planning department in Austin, the city function of planning, has a very low profile.

functions it appears to me to be rather reactionary and their direction seems to come solely from the council at the council's whim for instance there we do have a comprehensive plan which like many plans in texas has no real teeth to it and despite what the plan says the city is still building utilities
to sensitive environmental areas.

So there doesn't seem to be much, although the planning department exists and they do recommend basically zoning change, zoning change recommendations and subdivisions and they seem to want to check to make sure that the subdivision applicant has applied and has
crossed all his I's and dotted all his T's.
But they really don't do much planning.
Austin is a desirable city to live in.
Everyone comments about its environmental quality but from my viewpoint that is only pure circumstance and there is nothing within the city to protect what we have.
There is no ordinance which
that controls the cutting of trees.
There is a landscape ordinance which only speaks to putting grass and not covering a property from one property line to another with asphalt.
That's all it requires is that the property not be totally covered.
So you're drawing the distinction between the natural resource environment and the man-made environment.
Well, yes.
I understand what you mean by that question.
What I'm saying is...
When you're saying that Austin is considered by everyone to be desirable, you say it's a matter of circumstance or happenstance.
Yes.
The hills are beautiful.
Yeah, there's a natural resource base.
Right.
Yeah.
But then man has not done much to accommodate an enhancement of that.
Certainly not when the city council, as recommended by the planning department, approves...
a large shopping center to be built in the southwest hills.
And they have scalped the top of the hills and have two to one slopes that can never be maintained and have totally destroyed one of the natural scenic features.
Which area?
It's all the things we came here for.
Many of them are going to be quickly destroyed.
Is there any way to identify that area?
Oh, sure.
It's all been identified.
I mean, but what does it have a name?
Yeah, it does, really.
It's Barton Creek Mall or whatever it is.
And it's a Melvin Simons shopping center development.
And you've seen that shopping center over in College Station that they're developing.
And of course, the easiest way, most cost efficient way to develop a shopping center is to mow down everything and flatten the site.
And when you're trying to do that in the southwest hills of Austin, that's very difficult to do.
Is that the Tennessee firm?
No, they're from Ohio.
Ohio.
Yeah.
But it just seems like there are no real protections.
And planning is pretty weak.
If the mayor wants to see that something gets done, she'll see that it gets done and be damned with what the general plan says.
Although the general plan is very environmentally concerned.
And the general plan was, I think, done in a very, very good way, from what I understand, in terms of citizen participation.
And that general plan speaks to a north-south development corridor for Austin, period.

And you wouldn't see the city trying to put sewer and water lines to the southwest hills if there was any control over departments that meant that the department needed to comply with, generally speaking, with the general plan.
So the plan says this, but their policy is we go ahead
and do business over here as usual.
How many, how big a line do you want?
Do you have any responses to the transportation system, circulation system of Austin?
In terms of airports, freeways, thoroughfares, city streets, just getting around Austin, is that an easy thing to do?
It's not really.

The 41st Street, 38th and 12 Street, 35th Street corridor going east and west was identified years ago in a transportation plan as being a major, developed into a, upgraded into a major thoroughfare to sort of for crosstown traffic.
And the citizens didn't want that.
And I'm not sure it ever got there.
so far as to be any kind of conflict, but it never has been done.
And I'm not sure that it ever will.

The freeway, the Mopac Freeway, which is nearing its completion, or at least what they say is going to be the completed portion of it or the completed length of it, that has provided north-south transportation
in the western part of the city, and Interstate 35 fills that same function in the east part of the city.
In the north, there is Highway 183, which badly needs to be upgraded to a freeway standard.
Unfortunately, it really does.
And that's a function of the building permit process and zoning changes.
In other words, the city policy was to go ahead and allow all these businesses and subdivisions to develop out there, but all they had going to it was a four-lane highway.
with traffic lights and curb cuts.
What about Ben and White?
Ben and White sort of the same way.
It serves as a major thoroughfare, but it really almost needs to be a freeway.
So they sort of built what was improper.
And especially with a policy that says we'll approve any subdivision you want to build out here.
So there doesn't seem to be much coordination, again, between
the function of transportation planning, and the permit process to build something.
Tom, a city like Austin always has several projects going.
And Austin is, by Texas standards, an all city.
And presumably, they have small districts that need attention.
Could you describe perhaps some of the projects that are underway now that the city looks forward to benefiting by upgrading and rehabbing and so forth?
Well, probably the most outstanding feature of Austin is from an urban design standpoint and a historical standpoint as well is Congress Avenue and the entire downtown area.
many buildings dating to some of the very early structures built in Austin.
Many of which are undergoing adaptive reuse and at the same time others are demised by the arson's torch.
So we have some very strange things happening in downtown Austin.
But probably the most
prominent in the last couple of years has been the Congress Avenue redevelopment.
Congress Avenue is a broad six-lane street leading directly to the state capitol.
And there is a magnificent vista from the South Congress across the Colorado River to the capitol at the terminus of the avenue.
The street in
And almost just before the turn of the century, it was still a dirt street.
And despite the fact that they had some rather grand buildings built along the side of the avenue.
But over a period of years, everything seemed to get paved and sidewalks were built.
And what we ended up with was a rather dismal urban space leading to the most important structure in the state.
So about five years or so ago, and I believe this may have been also under the Friedman Council, which was a very active council, doing a lot of good things, it seems.
But they approved a renovation plan for Congress Avenue.
And the plan included several different phases.
One of the most important ones was flood control due to poor drainage conditions.
the avenue and buildings that had basements would frequently flood.
And so when I first came to Austin three years ago, they were just completing a giant storm sewer down the middle of Congress Avenue.
One would have thought they might have considered the inclusion of a rapid rail transit while they had the city street open, but they didn't.
That obviously was not part of the picture.
Or planned it maybe.
Yes, they hadn't planned that at all.

So at any rate, at this point, approximately six months ago, the city had completed an urban streetscape plan for Congress Avenue, which included trees and so forth, and widened sidewalks, other street amenities that
might be appropriate for a grand avenue leading to the state capitol.

Benches and drinking fountains and a small kiosk and a new sign system and traffic lights and so forth, all of which was to be designed, which was to be in keeping and to harmonize and so forth with the urban area.
The plans were completed by an architecture firm.
At the same time, it became knowledge of the general public that in order to accomplish the widened sidewalks and so forth, they were going to have to eliminate two lanes of traffic.
One lane in each direction.
One lane in each direction would be eliminated.
And this would accommodate the construction of tree wells and so forth, because many of the buildings have basements that extend out to the street curb under the sidewalk.
So in order to make everything consistent, we had to move out.

There were a number of downtown merchants who organized a campaign to not accept this particular plan, not to narrow the streets, not to eliminate approximately 50 or 60 parking places, which was going to have to occur.
Their basis, of course, was they were afraid they were going to lose business.
If one would walk down Congress Avenue, you would quickly identify Congress as a dying downtown business street with a lot of discount drugstores and other rather low-class types of businesses.
There are a few good stores that have hung on, such as Scarborough's and so forth.
This avenue also has several banks that face on it.
And several of the banks also felt that they didn't want to see the street narrowed.

you have to be familiar with the Texas banking laws to realize that a branch bank or a drive-in bank has to be within 500 feet or a thousand feet, some ridiculous distance close to the main bank, and therefore of course they were concerned that their customers would have difficulty getting to their drive-in bank.
That's why they were opposed to it.
So at any rate, what happened was the city, despite all the controversy and even controversy on the council, the mayor wanted to
block off a street with barricades and pretend like we had widened the sidewalks and see if we had a traffic problem.
Because the big hue and cry is, oh, we don't have any place for the automobiles to go.
Well, in fact, Congress, although it's a grand avenue, really doesn't go anyplace.
It's dead end at the capital end, so to speak.
And included in the plan, incidentally, was the changing of bus routes and so forth.
And, of course, the re-signaling and the total thing.

And at any rate, finally this group that opposed the whole plan, led by the merchants, decided that the only way they were going to stop the Congress Avenue renovation and the narrowing of the street, which was their point of contention, was to get up a referendum.
And they were successful in getting the 25% signatures of the last number of voters in an Austin election.
and presented their petition to the council, and their petition, the names were verified and so forth.
So the council was faced with either stopping the project totally or perhaps submitting it to the voters in the February election.
The council chose to, oh, the council had also accepted, had already advertised the project for bid, and the bids had been received.
The lowest bid was some million dollars over what the city had in hand that was actually earmarked for Congress Avenue.
However, there were other funds because it became prudent to include certain other types of renovation, for instance, the streetlight wiring system and so forth.
And so there were funds available from other city coffers to take up the difference.
But at any rate, what has happened is the project has been stopped at this point.
But I guess the interesting thing is not that Congress Avenue renovation has been thwarted by merchants who failed to see the benefits of it, which is partially true.
But in my view, I'm actually glad that it has stopped.
Because what Austin does not have, getting back to planning, is that Austin does not have a downtown plan.
Downtown is treated no differently than any other part of the city, and yet it functions in a very special way.
And if one is going to try to improve the conditions in the central business district, then there needs to be a plan from which one works from.
And you don't attack Congress Avenue as a separate and distinctive part of the downtown area.
It's part of the downtown area.
The city has...

A southeast corner of downtown is what's called the Rainy Street area, and in that area there are a lot of Chicano homes, and oh, probably about 40 or 50 of them, and many of them have been divided into apartments and so forth.
And so the Rainy Street area is part of downtown Austin.
Austin has the problem with the railroad tracks downtown, and they have done a separate study on the railroad tracks.
They have...
conditions along 6th Street and its potential business area of historic interest and significance.
That's a separate area.
So I guess what I'm saying is that... Where the Briscoe Hotel is.
Right, yes.
So what I'm saying is that here they are.
They're talking about this thing downtown.
They're talking about this thing downtown and this thing downtown, but they don't even have a plan.
And so what I say is we should first do a downtown plan

Oh, this also relates to about two years ago when the city council authorized, without real much public knowledge, a downtown redevelopment plan for the area from 3rd through 1st Street, which was the American Cities Plan.
So here are all these issues.
There's the American Cities Plan and the ire that that arrived.
That fell flat on its face.
Yes, exactly.
And they've got a real problem with this Rainey Street area because of the Chicano community and their feeling that they have a right to that part of downtown.
You have the conditions along 6th Street, which clearly need to be brought under control in terms of parking and other conditions along the avenue.
You have the Congress Avenue controversy and problems.
So here we have a whole number of issues that all are downtown.
Oh, the railroads.
What are we going to do about the railroads?
We're going to get rid of the railroads and utilize that area in some other way.
So you have a whole bunch of problems down there that have never been attacked from a planning standpoint at all.
Certainly not comprehensively.
And we just do a little bit here, a little bit there.
And these little tries you see fail.
It seems to me that downtown Austin has an interesting juxtaposition of...
features such as Town Lake with the beautiful lake, a civic auditorium on one side.
It has a park strip that runs along it, which is ideal.
It is not that far away from the state capitol.
It is adjacent to the CBD.
All of these things come together, and this is going to cause some pressure for certain types of development.
which may or may not be in the long-range interests of the citizens of Austin.
And it's going to be interesting to see how the area immediately adjacent to Turner Lake on the North Shore is redeveloped in the coming decades.
What would be the objective of that particular area for redevelopment south, for example, of where the railroad tracks are now?
Well, it has a...
Right now, there's no demand for it.
That's probably the saving grace.
But at the same time, there's also no plan for it.
And I suppose that several planning postures would be obvious.
And probably the major one that would relate best to the lake and that amenity would be the development of residential, highly residential
in the first couple of blocks along Town Lake.
A city where the same kind of conditions sort of exist would be the shoreline along Lake Michigan in Chicago.
where there was a heavy concentration along the North Shore of residential use.
Now, obviously, there's quite a bit of difference between Lake Michigan and Town Lake and Chicago and Austin, Texas.
So maybe we're talking about small townhouse types of structures, two and three story, which would fit in quite well.

with an area of green developed along the lake and then you move closer to north toward the capital and you get into the central business district where there are offices and other businesses where many of the people living in this area work so you have the possibility for a very concentrated pretty pedestrian oriented downtown austin and in fact you have two um nice
amenities of both sort of the north and south end of downtown Austin.
You have the Capitol on one side and you have Town Lake on the other.
And with the Shoal Creek Hike and Bike Trail and the Waller Creek Hike and Bike Trail, you have two nice pedestrian things that bring you all the way down.
So there are, you know, some good potential.
But the only interest so far along Town Lake has been, for instance, the Holiday Inn wanted to exchange parkland for money
with the city and take part of the town lake to build another high rise tower and a parking garage.
Fortunately, that idea just really met with disdain.
And it would have set a very dangerous precedent for the city to have even a long term lease arrangement.
That's what the hotel said, we'll buy it, we'll lease it from you, we just want this land.
It just happened to be park.
So, unfortunately that didn't happen.
I think the main problem here is that there is no way that the general plan, although it is adopted, but it has no teeth in forcing the council to follow it.
And I'm not quite sure of the actual procedure of adoption and what that means.
I'm sure Dick Lilly can tell you.
But the city council, there's nothing that forces the city council to do it.
So a very good master plan.

drawn up under a previous council who was very environmentally oriented, hits a council that is not environmentally oriented, but is oriented toward growth at whatever cost, oriented toward serving the development community.
I know a developer who told me that when Friedman Council came in, he went to San Antonio, built houses down there for four years.
And as soon as McTowell got in, he moved right back to Austin, because that's where he wanted to be.
He just couldn't do business here with Friedman.
I think that there's no way that the comprehensive plan can have any continuity to it, even if under the present conditions, because there's no way that it's continuous.
It just depends on the council and which way they're going to look.
I think Austin has a number of problems, because I don't think there's enough concern for the environment here that makes the city that people
think of it as.
It's a beautiful place to be, but gee, I can take you to a lot of places and you won't find it very pretty.
And the things that are here are things that we're not even protecting.
We're very happy to let Simon's build his mall out there that is over the aquifer that furnishes water for Barton Springs.
And that much of the shopping center land drains to the Barton Springs watershed.
And we're not even concerned about that.
There has been some good activity in planning with regard to growth controls along Town Lake.
And there has been, most recently, but only after real public assistance by private groups, say Barton Creek, Barton Springs, and other groups, has there been any control.
